Name: fairfax_county_2007_spot
Abstract: This layer contains spot elevations for land and water features. The land spots contain the elevation for that particular point on the ground. The water spots contain the elevation of the water body. Spot elevations were captured for tops of hills ( including dams ), depressions, saddles, intersection of roads, center lines of roads over culverts, center and end of bridges, intersection of roads and railroads, and in areas of dense vegetation where the ground is visible.

    <descript>
      <abstract>This layer contains spot elevations for land and water features. The land spots contain the elevation for that particular point on the ground. The water spots contain the elevation of the water body. Spot elevations were captured for tops of hills ( including dams ), depressions, saddles, intersection of roads, center lines of roads over culverts, center and end of bridges, intersection of roads and railroads, and in areas of dense vegetation where the ground is visible.</abstract>
      <purpose>This layers was created to depict precise ( 90% = 1.25 feet ) elevation at specific points on the earth. There are also no spots that are greater than 7.5 feet in error.</purpose>
    </descript>

  <dataqual>
    <attracc>
      <attraccr>The draw symbol attribute was checked by plotting the features on the standard map product and ensuring the features appeared and were drawn correctly. The elevation attributes were check by randomly selecting a set and sending surveyors into the field to verify the positional accuracy of the locations.  Automated routines and visual checking procedures developed by Engineering Systems were used to check the attributes.</attraccr>
    </attracc>
    <logic>Logical consistency was tested by visual inspection and automated quality control procedures. There are no duplicate points.</logic>
    <complete>Data set is considered complete for the information presented, as described in the abstract. Users are advised to read the rest of the metadata record carefully for additional details.</complete>
    <posacc>
      <horizpa>
        <horizpar>Horizontal positional accuracy for the digital data is tested by visual comparison of the source with hard copy plots. The data was also compared to the digital ortho photography. A random set of points were provided to survey branch to go in the field and verify positional accuracy of the spots.</horizpar>
      </horizpa>
      <vertacc>
        <vertaccr>Vertical positional accuracy for the digital data is tested by random field verification of known points. Data was also compared to the digital terrain model by overlaying the contours with the tins and spot checking elevations.</vertaccr>
      </vertacc>
    </posacc>

      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Data copied from the CD obtained from Fairfax County, VA 2007.
The planimetric features were stereocompiled from the controlled set of 1''=660? scale photography.  Each map feature was captured in a specific and consistent manner.  All data is geo-referenced at the time of compilation, ensuring the integration of the photogrammetric models into the County Tax Map grid system.</procdesc>
        <procdate>1997-1998</procdate>
        <proccont>
          <cntinfo>
            <cntorgp>
              <cntorg>Fairfax County GIS and Mapping Services</cntorg>
            </cntorgp>
            <cntpos>Database Administrator</cntpos>
            <cntaddr>
              <addrtype>mailing and physical address</addrtype>
              <address>12000 Government Center Pw. Suite 117</address>
              <city>Fairfax</city>
              <state>VA</state>
              <postal>22035</postal>
              <country>USA</country>
            </cntaddr>
            <cntvoice>(703)-324-2712</cntvoice>
            <cntfax>(703)-324-3937</cntfax>
            <cntemail>gis.helpq@fairfaxcounty.gov</cntemail>
          </cntinfo>
        </proccont>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Set the compilation model on analytical stereo plotters</procdesc>
        <srcused>SPOT1</srcused>
        <procdate>1997-1998</procdate>
        <srcprod>SPOT2</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Digitize planimetric features into a file</procdesc>
        <srcused>SPOT2</srcused>
        <procdate>1997-1998</procdate>
        <srcprod>SPOT3</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Translate the raw digitized data into APS (ASI’s internal processing software)</procdesc>
        <srcused>SPOT3</srcused>
        <procdate>1997-1998</procdate>
        <srcprod>SPOT4</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Check for validation errors (i.e. arcs with only two points or invalid feature code/element type combinations and delete “empty” features such as annotation with no printable characters in the text string</procdesc>
        <srcused>SPOT4</srcused>
        <procdate>1997-1998</procdate>
        <srcprod>SPOT5</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Snap graphic features to other as necessary, offset features the required distances and break features with others.</procdesc>
        <srcused>SPOT5</srcused>
        <procdate>1997-1998</procdate>
        <srcprod>SPOT6</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Load all necessary models for a particular tile and extract all planimetric feature data within that tile’s boundary</procdesc>
        <srcused>SPOT6</srcused>
        <procdate>1997-1998</procdate>
        <srcprod>SPOT7</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Tile is plotted at 1''=200’ for manual edit checks.  Plot is checked for correct capture of all required features types, missing features and mis-snapped linework and unsnapped linework.  Attributes and annotation are placed on the check plot for entry into the database.</procdesc>
        <srcused>SPOT7</srcused>
        <procdate>1997-1998</procdate>
        <srcprod>SPOT8</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>First graphic edit.  All errors noted are corrected, attributes and annotation are placed, general topology check, building all polygons for the appropriate coverage's, check for dangles, redundant lines and duplicate or missing label points.</procdesc>
        <srcused>SPOT8</srcused>
        <procdate>1997-1998</procdate>
        <srcprod>SPOT9</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Second graphic edit.  All polygon coverage's are rebuilt in batch mode with errors being flagged and text is generated from the attributes found on certain planimetric layers.</procdesc>
        <srcused>SPOT9</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>SPOT10</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Translation. This is a two step process.  First step transforms all graphic elements along with their associated attributes into ArcInfo format.  The second step enters into Arcedit and performs “builds” and joins as required for each coverage, removes pseudo nodes and copies the projection file to each coverage.</procdesc>
        <srcused>SPOT10</srcused>
        <procdate>1997-1998</procdate>
        <srcprod>SPOT11</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>ArcInfo QC. Checks for the existence and validity of all required coverage's, proper item definitions, attributes with valid values and correct annotation sizes and subclass/level definitions.  This also checks for data along the edges of the coverage to ensure that all data ties to the adjoining files both in location and in attribute values.</procdesc>
        <srcused>SPOT11</srcused>
        <procdate>1997-1998</procdate>
        <srcprod>SPOT12</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Color check plots are created of the tile with the full set of planimetric and topographic features.</procdesc>
        <srcused>SPOT12</srcused>
        <procdate>1997-1998</procdate>
        <srcprod>SPOT13</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Data is reviewed by on site quality control contractor, Engineering Systems.  The quality control review combines both automated and manual checks.  Automated checks of the coverage's to ensure that all coverage's existed with the correct data structure and that the attributes existed with valid data.  Manual checks of the data included review of the information overlaid on the digital orthophotography to check for completeness and accuracy as per the specifications of the RFP</procdesc>
        <srcused>SPOT13</srcused>
        <procdate/>
        <srcprod>SPOT14</srcprod>
      </procstep>
      <procstep>
        <procdesc>Metadata imported.</procdesc>
        <srcused>C:\DOCUME~1\gthoma\LOCALS~1\Temp\xml84D.tmp</srcused>
        <procdate/>
      </procstep>

      <fees>Property & Topography Data

This data set includes over 30 layers of attributed vector property, planimetric, and contour data that were derived primarily from survey plats and orthophotography.

The Countywide Property & Topography 4 CD set in Coverage format sells for $2850.

The Countywide Property & Topography 3 CD set in Shapefile format sells for $2850.

Property & Topography by Map Grid Tile data on CD is available in Coverage or Shapefile fomat.
There is a $25 base charge per order plus an additonal fee of $13 per tax map grid tile.
